{"source_key":"sha256-0bac065cc2ac145cc8e9eb2125aa5b14","record_index":15,"record_hash":"sha256:dfa4078dc01b1530b8fc74e916a77daa709fed2a05a2ee4862d85746f6efb3d6","timestamp":"2026-05-26T19:23:00.794Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: e53880\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 2263\nOutput:\n# Maintainability Playbook\n\nUse this playbook for a focused cleanup pass after a feature or fix is working.\nIt is not a second spec. The implementation contract, product requirements, and\ntests still win. The point is to make the code smaller, clearer, and easier for\nthe next maintainer to change.\n\nThis works best for code that was built quickly, touched by agents, or grew a\nlittle too much ceremony while the behavior was still moving.\n\n## Source Material\n\nUseful references behind this playbook:\n\n- [Google Engineering Practices: What to look for in a code review](https://google.github.io/eng-practices/review/reviewer/looking-for.html)\n- [Rust API Guidelines checklist](https://rust-lang.github.io/api-guidelines/checklist.html)\n- [GitHub: Review AI-generated code](https://docs.github.com/en/copilot/tutorials/review-ai-generated-code)\n- [Martin Fowler: Code Smell](https://martinfowler.com/bliki/CodeSmell.html)\n- [Refactoring Guru: Speculative Generality](https://refactoring.guru/smells/speculative-generality)\n- [Claude Code best practices](https://code.claude.com/docs/en/best-practices)\n- [Simon Willison: First run the tests](https://simonwillison.net/guides/agentic-engineering-patterns/first-run-the-tests/)\n\n## Specialize First\n\nBefore reviewing, fill in the local facts for the subsystem in your head or in a\nshort note:\n\n- **Target:** the files, crate, package, service, or feature being reviewed.\n- **Behavior contract:** what must stay true.\n- **Primary entry points:** commands, routes, jobs, public APIs, or UI flows.\n- **Owned boundaries:** modules that should own parsing, orchestration, storage,\n  external calls, rendering, validation, or redaction.\n- **Validation commands:** the narrow checks that prove this area still works.\n- **Known non-goals:** cleanup that would become a redesign.\n\nExample:\n\n```text\nTarget: crates/foo/src/projection.rs\nContract: public output stays allowlisted and bounded\nEntry po\n[TRUNCATED]\n actual\ncontract.\n\n### 7. AI-Specific Review Pass\n\nAsk reviewers or subagents narrow questions:\n\n- What looks over-generalized for the problem we know exists?\n- What would a maintainer misunderstand six months from now?\n- Which name hides a concrete domain concept?\n- Which public field is only present because it was easy to echo?\n- Which test would still pass if the behavior were subtly wrong?\n- Which helper, dependency, module, or DTO exists only because generated code\n  tends to over-structure things?\n- Which public field could leak private state, local paths, raw payloads, or\n  debug vocabulary?\n\nDo not ask for a broad rewrite. The output should be small findings, not a new\narchitecture.\n\n## Cleanup Recipe\n\n### Step 0. Establish The Baseline\n\nRun the narrow checks before changing code. Use the project's real commands.\n\nExamples:\n\n```text\ncargo fmt --check\ncargo test -p <crate> <focused-test-name>\ncargo check -p <crate-or-bin> --features <feature>\ncargo clippy -p <crate> --all-targets --no-deps\npnpm test <package>\npnpm lint <package>\ngo test ./...\n```\n\nIf the baseline is already broken, fix or document that separately before\nstarting cleanup. A cleanup pass should not hide pre-existing failures.\n\n### Step 1. Main Agent Reads The Code\n\nThe main agent should read the target code first:\n\n- entry point files\n- orchestration files\n- domain modules\n- persistence/external-call modules\n- serialization/projection/rendering modules\n- nearby tests\n\nThen follow one concrete invocation through the subsystem. Keep this as a short\ncall-chain note, not a design document.\n\nDo not spawn subagents yet. The main agent needs enough context to judge whether\nsubagent feedback is useful or generic.\n\n### Step 2. Spawn Focused Review Subagents\n\nUse subagents for independent review, not implementation, at this stage. Give\neach subagent a narrow lens and ask for findings only.\n\nRecommended subagents:\n\n- **Deletion reviewer:** find fake extensibility, one-use helpers, dead fields,\n  ceremonial modules, and comments that repeat code.\n","tool_name":"exec_command","tool_kind":"exec","tool_input":null,"exit_code":0,"outcome":"succeeded","source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-26T19:23:00.794Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}